mme. The Best Part Of Radhanagar Beach Sea walking Parasailing Scuba diving and Snorkelling Birdwatching Swimming Nearby Attractions 2. Cellular Jail Port Blair, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands capital, has a historic colonial jail known as The Cellular Jail, often known as "Kala Pani." Several significant freedom fighters, like Yogendra Shukla, Vinayak Damodar Savarkar, and Batukeshwar Dutt, stayed. The prison complex is currently controlled by the Indian government and is recognized as a national war memorial representing prisoner life during the British colonial era. The Cellular Jail in the Andaman Islands is a well-known tourist attraction where visitors may learn about its history and enjoy a light show created in honour of all the prisoners housed there. The Cellular Jail, an essential part of India's history, serves as a sad memory of all the difficulties Indian freedom fighters suffered while pursuing their war for independence. Tip For Visit There is a high fee of INR 200 to carry your camera inside the museum's grounds. Follow the instructor so that you may better understand the museum's history. The Best Thing about Cellular Jail Cellular Jail Memorial The architecture of Cellular Jail Cellular Jail Light and Sound Show 3. Ross Island Ross Island, formerly known as Netaji Subhash Bose Island, was originally the British government's administrative centre but is now merely a deserted island located barely two kilometres east of Port Blair. The British evacuated Ross Island in 1941 due to an earthquake, moving their settlement to Port Blair. It is hard to imagine at first glance that this deserted island was once the centre of British authority and included a bazaar, a church, shops, a bakery, a water treatment plant, a tennis court, a printing press, a secretariat, a hospital, a cemetery, and other essential institutions. Everything has vanished except a few structures that once held some of these sites. Some historic structures, including neighbourhood sh