an Mondays, as there are no ferry services to Jolly Buoy Island on that day. Unless you obtain a permit from the Fisheries Department, you may bring no seashell. Jolly Buoy Island is a plastic-free zone, so make sure you don't bring any plastic items, such as carry bags. 11. Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex The charming Andaman Islands provide a wide range of tourist activities to ensure visitors have a good experience. Among these locations, the Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex is a must-see spot for explorers. The region offers a wide variety of thrilling water sports activities and is known as the Andaman Water Sports Complex. The Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex offers a variety of sports, including paddle boats, banana boats, row boats, parasailing, speed boats, scuba diving, Snorkelling, and more. While Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex attracts tourists, it also has historical value. In 1859, this was the scene of the Battle of Aberdeen, a conflict between British troops and Andaman natives. If you're too unwilling to engage in any water sports offered at Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex, visit there instead to see the war monument. A well-known area for child activities is a nearby children's park. Best Time For Visit When Andaman and Nicobar Island is experiencing its winter season, October and March is the ideal time to visit Rajiv Gandhi Water Sports Complex. Time: Every day of the week, 10:00 am to 6:00 pm. 12. Mahatma Gandhi Marine National Park The Wildlife Protection Act of 1972 established the Mahatma Gandhi Marine National Park on May 24, 1983. Primarily to preserve aquatic life, including the area's many nesting sea turtles and magnificent coral reefs made it. On the southwest shore, Mahatma Gandhi Marine National Park is a marine life-protected area located 25 kilometres from Port Blair, the Andaman Islands' main city; on the southwest shore is also known as Wandur National Park. Its surroundings are stunning, crystal-clear water, pure white s