 is also safe. For visitors best time to visit:?Avoid visiting during the rainy season between September and February or between March and May. Services Both male and female changing rooms are provided. For a day may be rented locker facilities for INR 10 per locker. Travel agent There are paid showers available for INR 10 per person. Basic knowledge: According to Times magazine, this seventh-greatest beach in the world is the best in Asia. It is also referred to as Port Blair's Beach No. 7. The beach has been recognized with a Blue Flag Certificate by the United Nations Environment Programme. The Best Part Of Radhanagar Beach Sea walking Parasailing Scuba diving and Snorkelling Birdwatching Swimming Nearby Attractions 2. Cellular Jail Port Blair, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands capital, has a historic colonial jail known as The Cellular Jail, often known as "Kala Pani." Several significant freedom fighters, like Yogendra Shukla, Vinayak Damodar Savarkar, and Batukeshwar Dutt, stayed. The prison complex is currently controlled by the Indian government and is recognized as a national war memorial representing prisoner life during the British colonial era. The Cellular Jail in the Andaman Islands is a well-known tourist attraction where visitors may learn about its history and enjoy a light show created in honour of all the prisoners housed there. The Cellular Jail, an essential part of India's history, serves as a sad memory of all the difficulties Indian freedom fighters suffered while pursuing their war for independence. Tip For Visit There is a high fee of INR 200 to carry your camera inside the museum's grounds. Follow the instructor so that you may better understand the museum's history. The Best Thing about Cellular Jail Cellular Jail Memorial The architecture of Cellular Jail Cellular Jail Light and Sound Show 3. Ross Island Ross Island, formerly known as Netaji Subhash Bose Island, was originally the British government's administrative centre but is now merely a deserted island located barely two kilometres east of Port Blair. The British evacuated Ross Island in 1941 due to an earthquake, moving their settlement to Port Blair. It is hard to imagine at first glance that this deserted island was once the centre of British authority and included a bazaar, a church, shops, a bakery, a water treatment plant, a tennis court, a printing press, a secretariat, a hospital, a cemetery, and other essential institutions. Everything has vanished except a few structures that once held some of these sites. Some historic structures, including neighbourhood shops, and bakeries, have been successfully rebuilt by the Indian Navy to give tourists a sense of the past. These stores also sell goods. Tip For Visit Most visitors to the island only stay for two to three hours. Take the 4:00 pm boat trip to the island to get there in time if you want to see the Light and Sound Show on the island. The Best of Ross Island Visit the Sanctuary Experience the Ross Island Light and Sound Show Explore the Ruins Japanese Bunker 4. Neil Island Ritchie's Archipelago includes Neill Island, a South Andaman Administrative District component in the Bay of Bengal. Ross Island and Havelock Island are separated from it by a portion of the vast ocean, and Neill Island is a popular day trip for visitors to Havelock Island. The three sandy beaches on this island, Bharatpur Beach, Sitapur Beach, and Lakshmanpur Beach, are its most charming characteristic. A part of the island's northwest is carefully maintained, although rice farming has significantly decreased the island's forest area. The temperature is a few degrees higher in areas where the forest cover has been destroyed than in regions with suitable plants. However, Neill Island is the primary source of vegetables for most of the Andaman Islands. Neill Island is a small island that may be explored by walking. All three beaches are beautiful and have benefits to the island. Best Time For A Visit The perfect time to visit Neill Island in the Andaman is in the winter, mainly between October and February. The Best of Neil Island Laxmanpur Beach 1 Laxmanpur Beach 2 Sitapur Beach 5. Snorkeling in Andaman The Andaman Islands' unique location in the Indian Ocean provides a fantastic opportunity for Snorkelling. Various facilities supply the necessary snorkelling gear in addition to brief instructions. For the beginning, intermediate, and experienced swimmers, they provide a variety of programs. Through the aquatic sport of Snorkelling, swimmers may view marine life without going deep underwater or carrying costly equipment. The main item of kit needed for Snorkelling is a diving mask with glasses and a 30-centimetre long tube known as a snorkel. Swimmers can observe as much of the underwater world while remaining relatively near to the water's surface. Tip for visit Follow the local weather prediction for that day. Swimming requires understanding the ocean, the wind, and their behaviour. To prevent disasters in the water, one must try for a good fit if they must rent the equipment. Avoid touch with any marine life. Always swim with others, or bring a snorkelling companion or a knowledgeable guide. 6. Mount Harriet National Park Mount Harriet National Park, one of the nine national parks held by Andaman Island, is the most stunning. The third-highest peak (365 meters) in Andaman and Nicobar is Mount Harriet, situated in Ferrargunj Tehsil of Port Blair, and it is also the most readily reached. The national park may find animals and birds of different species, which is 46.62 square kilometres in size. Due to its advantageous height, the park provides stunning views of the island's blue waters and exciting sunrise and sunset experiences. Tip For Visit For overnight stays, tents are provided. Playground for children Tourist cottages and inns are available Snack shops are not here, so take your proper meal with you. There are public restrooms accessible. Attractions? The Madhuban Beach, the Orchidarium, and the Butterfly House 7. Water Sports in Andamans The region's water sports have attracted adventurers and water lovers to the Andaman Islands. The Andaman Islands have a few areas where the desire for water sports is satisfied; there is something for everyone if they prefer swimming, Snorkelling, scuba diving, fishing, or just taking a boat trip. For the variety and protection that it provides, the Port Blair Water Sports Complex is well-known. If one has the courage, they may sail around Port Blair's allowed shoreline on their own while the staff keeps an eye on them. No activities need swimming so that visitors can enrol in them without concerns. Rajiv Gandhi Nagar in Port Blair, Andaman, is where the Water Sports Complex is situated. The Andaman Water Sports Centre is close to Port Blair's northern shoreline and Aberdeen Jetty. Adventure seekers may engage in activities like paddle boating, kayaking, banana boat rides, parasailing, rowing, and more at the facility's designated water sports area on the Andaman Sea. They offer all the services required for a secure and joyful experience. Snorkelling, Scuba diving, and underwater walking are popular water sports in this area. One of the limited locations in India that provide these water sports services is this one. 8. Baratang Island A stunning tiny island in the North and Middle Andaman Administrative District, Baratang Island, often referred to as Ranchiwalas Island, is located around 100 kilometres from Port Blair by road. Mangroves Creeks, limestone caverns, and mud volcanoes (only ones in India) are among the island's best-known natural features. You might need permission from the Baratang Forest Department to visit limestone caves. Baratang Island, in contrast to Havelock Island, is mainly used as a centre for natural viewing because it is less developed for urban tourism. The government boat service that connects Port Blair city and Phoenix Bay Jetty permits visitors to get to Baratang 